      </section>

      <section>
        <title><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#808080" -->Note
        down nomination</title>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Ask
        every circle member to note down silently who they would like to
        nominate. Tell everyone that they can nominate themselves!</para>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Ideally,
        everyone notes down their nominations for each role (like on paper or
        in a private message) so everyone can form their original idea without
        getting distracted by the others’ opinions. There is value in people’s
        original ideas, so let’s hear them.</para>
      </section>

      <section>
        <title><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#808080" -->Nomination
        round</title>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Ask
        everyone in a round to share who they nominate for which role and why.
        Ideally, reasons for nominations refer back to the qualifications.
        (Ask people to refrain from mentioning who they <emphasis
        role="from-text">don’t</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->
        nominate because it’s typically not useful to do that.)</para>
      </section>

      <section>
        <title><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#808080" -->Change
        round</title>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->After
        the nomination round, do another round where people can change their
        nominations. If they change their nomination, they may want to share
        new insights that led them to changing their nomination. Be sure to
        let them know that it is not necessary to have full convergence – not
        everyone needs to nominate same person per role to continue.</para>
      </section>

      <section>
        <title><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#808080" -->Propose
        a candidate and find consent</title>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->The
        facilitator makes sure that a candidate is being proposed for each
        role. The easiest way to ensure that is to make a proposal.
        Alternatively, the facilitator can ask someone else to make a proposal
        and ask for consent. For example, this could sound like this: “I
        propose that Michelle be the leader of this group for six months, I be
        facilitator also for six months, and Marco be the secretary for six
        months. Are there any objections? Remember that you object if you have
        reasons to assume that we can’t fulfill our aim with that person in
        that role.” (Find more details and examples in <emphasis
        role="from-text">Many Voices One Song</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->,
        Chapter 3.6.)</para>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->If
        there are objections, try to integrate. For example, if an objection
        is that someone might not have enough time, propose a different
        candidate, shorten the original candidate’s term, or see if you can
        free that person up to serve this role. If the objection is that
        someone does not have enough experience, see if you can give them
        extra training, or shorten the term.</para>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Some
        groups try to rotate or split roles. Both of those strategies reduce
        the clarity of who does what. As an alternative, we recommend having
        short terms (like three months) so that more people can hold roles
        over time but the first ‘officers’ can grow into their role.</para>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->You
        now have a facilitator, leader, and secretary! Celebrate and thank
        them! They may start their job immediately or at the next meeting.
        Ideally, the facilitator is familiar with this booklet. If not,
        support them in following the process.</para>
      </section>
    </section>

    <section>
      <title><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#46818D" font="sansserif" -->Infrastructure
      and communication</title>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Each
      circle requires a little bit of infrastructure for circle documents and
      email addresses or handles. It creates unnecessary friction if the
      documents are all over the place or if some circle members are forgotten
      in our communication because we hit “reply all” in just too many
      different email threads.</para>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->So
      while this item might be small and easy, it’s important nonetheless. To
      speed things up, you, as the convener, can bring a proposal to the
      meeting. Here is an example proposal for you to start from:</para>

      <para><quote><!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->This
      circle will communicate using email. Our secretary will create a …and
      make sure all members are included. All circle documents (lists,
      minutes, and reference documents) will be in the …folder (link). Within
      that folder, there will be one meeting minutes document that collects
      all minutes in the same document. At the top of that document will be
      the <emphasis role="bold">backlog</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->
      (= the list of future agenda items) of the circle. <!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Term:
      6 months</quote></para>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->The
      idea is to be as clear and practical as possible with as little extra
      overhead as possible while finding a solution that includes all
      members.</para>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->For
      your proposal, follow the typical consent process of presenting the
      proposal/clarifying questions, quick reactions, and consent.</para>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Once
      you have established the backlog, here are two items you can already put
      onto the backlog:<itemizedlist>
          <listitem>
            <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->selection
            process (date: whenever the terms are up that you’ve set in the
            selection process);</para>
          </listitem>

          <listitem>
            <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->review
            communication and circle documents policy (date; whenever the term
            is up that you’ve set just now)</para>
          </listitem>
        </itemizedlist></para>
    </section>

    <section>
      <title><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#46818D" font="sansserif" -->Gather
      items for the backlog</title>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->The
      next task is fun again! You get to fill that backlog with a lot of
      exciting ideas!</para>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Given
      your aim and expertise, what are the topics or questions you will have
      to address? Problems you will have to solve? By that, I mean concrete,
      doable things. It might help to prompt these by starting people off by
      saying <emphasis role="from-text">“How might we…?”</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" --></para>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Do
      this in rounds. Ideally, every person offers only one or two at a time,
      and you do several rounds. That way, you can weave the circle member’s
      interests together already, as people build on each other’s
      ideas.</para>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Have
      the secretary write those ideas into the backlog. That’s where those
      backlog items will live until we can address them.</para>
    </section>

    <section>
      <title><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#46818D" font="sansserif" -->Prioritize
      the backlog</title>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->You
      can’t do everything at once. And that’s frustrating! Within your group,
      there might be disagreement on what needs to be dealt with first. Quite
      a few groups go down the unfortunate rabbit hole of arguing over what is
      more important. For example, I have witnessed groups that got slowed
      down because they could not decide whether to focus on topic A <emphasis
      role="from-text">or</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->
      B. Instead of making a plan of how to get <emphasis
      role="from-text">both</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->,
      they got neither because they argued and tried to persuade each other
      that one was more important.</para>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->What
      do I mean when I say “both”? Well, it is possible to work on two things
      at once, for example, by reserving the same amount of time at the next
      meeting. (Or you can form two teams and put each on one task.)</para>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->What
      you need is an action plan on what to tackle first. For now, the task is
      to prioritize the list and pick three items from your backlog to start
      on. The process we will use here is a version of a process you did
      earlier: the selection process.</para>

      <section>
        <title><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#808080" -->Step-by-step</title>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->The
        goal is to pick around three items from your backlog. You are not
        solving them yet. You are just selecting which ones you are spending
        time and effort on first.</para>

        <para><itemizedlist>
            <listitem>
              <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->First,
              ask everyone if they’d like to include something on the backlog.
              Maybe there was a new idea or opportunity.</para>
            </listitem>

            <listitem>
              <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Now
              ask everyone to (quietly) nominate three items and note them
              down.</para>
            </listitem>

            <listitem>
              <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Everyone
              shares in a round what items they picked and why. (Nomination
              round)</para>
            </listitem>

            <listitem>
              <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->After
              that first round, ask people if they’d like to change their
              minds on some of their nominations. (Change round)</para>
            </listitem>

            <listitem>
              <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Make
              a proposal (or ask someone else to make one) of three items to
              tackle first. Make a good faith effort to represent the energy
              of the circle.</para>
            </listitem>

            <listitem>
              <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Find
              consent on that proposal. Objections need to point out how the
              group won’t fulfill its aim if the topic is not among the first
              three topics addressed. To address objections, you might have to
              modify, e.g. add a 4th item, or merge items or add a
              waitlist.</para>
            </listitem>
          </itemizedlist></para>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->If
        you have enough time, do a round and see if you can find ways to
        prepare those agenda items for your third meeting to make sure you can
        actually make a decision about them. For example, if there are
        preparatory documents, make sure to share those. Or something needs to
        be researched (like grants you could apply for), assign it to a person
        or a group. That way, you’re already super prepared next time you
        meet!</para>

        <informalfigure>
          <mediaobject>
            <imageobject>
              <imagedata fileref="illustrations/Image20.png" width="100%"/>
            </imageobject>
          </mediaobject>
        </informalfigure>
      </section>
    </section>

    <section xml:id="newmembers">
      <title><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#46818D" font="sansserif" -->Add
      new members?</title>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->You’re
      almost done! One open question that is still leftover from last time is
      the question of whether additional people should join your group right
      now and, if so, who.</para>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->To
      make this decision, first, decide whether you want new people to join at
      all. The easiest way to find out is to propose:</para>

      <para><quote><!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Proposal:
      I propose to select up to …<emphasis role="from-text">x</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->
      people to add to the circle.</quote></para>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Follow
      the typical pattern of presenting the proposal and allowing clarifying
      questions, quick reactions round, and consent round.</para>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->If
      someone objects – for example, because they worry that the group will be
      too big or for other reasons – and there is no obvious way to integrate
      it, let it go and move to the closing.</para>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->If
      everyone consents, you add another quick selection process like in the
      previous agenda item.</para>

      <para><itemizedlist>
          <listitem>
            <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Ask
            everyone to decide silently who they will nominate.</para>
          </listitem>

          <listitem>
            <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Now
            ask everyone to share in a round who they picked and why. Since
            not everyone will know the same people, make sure to give people a
            chance to ask questions about that person. (Nomination
            round)</para>
          </listitem>

          <listitem>
            <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->After
            that first round, ask people if they’d like to change their minds
            on some of their nominations. (Change round)</para>
          </listitem>

          <listitem>
            <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->The
            facilitator now makes a proposal (or asks someone else to).
            Whoever picks the proposal makes a good faith effort to represent
            where the energy is in the circle.</para>
          </listitem>

          <listitem>
            <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Find
            consent. Remind people that if they wanted a person that didn’t
            get proposed this time, it’s not a “no forever” but just a “not
            yet,” and that group cohesion and intentional growth are important
            to start out well.</para>
          </listitem>
        </itemizedlist><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Note:
      there are three categories of people who you might want to
      add:<itemizedlist>
          <listitem>
            <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->People
            who you know and want in because you think they are a great
            addition to the group.</para>
          </listitem>

          <listitem>
            <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->People
            who you know and you would like to add as the group grows and
            forms additional sub-groups, for example, because they have
            expertise in a relevant field.</para>
          </listitem>

          <listitem>
            <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->People
            who you don’t know yet but who will bring skill sets that you
            don’t have covered in your group.</para>
          </listitem>
        </itemizedlist><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->In
      this meeting, I would only focus on the first group until you have
      additional sub-groups or needs.</para>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->After
      the last agenda items, be sure to ask for new ideas for the backlog
      before you go to the closing round.</para>
    </section>

