      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->The
      agenda items for the teal row are:<itemizedlist>
          <listitem>
            <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Integrate
            new members (if applicable)</para>
          </listitem>

          <listitem>
            <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Form
            sub-circles, or roles?</para>
          </listitem>

          <listitem>
            <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Operationalize
            priority item #1</para>
          </listitem>

          <listitem>
            <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Operationalize
            priority item #2</para>
          </listitem>

          <listitem>
            <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Operationalize
            priority item #3</para>
          </listitem>

          <listitem>
            <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Review
            processes so far.</para>
          </listitem>
        </itemizedlist></para>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->The
      priority items #1-3 are the items that the circle prioritized in meeting
      #2. If you selected two or four priority items, then you now have
      accordingly, more agenda items today.</para>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->For
      all the standard agenda items in grey (check-in, ADMIN, Consent to the
      agenda, update backlog, and check-out), please refer to the last
      chapter. Everything is the same, today and forever! (Until you decide to
      change it…, but how about you stick with it and enjoy the good process
      forever?)</para>
    </section>

    <section>
      <title><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#46818D" font="sansserif" -->Integrate
      new members</title>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->If
      you invited new members to this meeting, do a round where the current
      members give the new members a short version of who they are. Ideally,
      you’ve taken notes the last time, and the new member can read up on the
      details.</para>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Now
      let the new member introduce themselves. Take notes. If you want to plan
      well into the future, make a section in the agenda notes under the
      backlog and copy the information from the first meeting when people
      introduced themselves and their previous experiences. Now add to that
      list the new members’ information. Tada! A simple member directory will
      make onboarding easier until we need something more sophisticated. To
      comply with privacy laws, find a place where you can store the
      information.</para>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->When
      the new member has spoken, and you have extra time, make sure people can
      ask the new person questions; then do a reaction round where everyone
      can say something to the new person. (Mostly, that’s words of
      welcome.)</para>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Ask
      for consent to welcoming that person into the circle. By consenting, the
      incoming member consents to their own membership the circle’s aim, and
      the chosen process.</para>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->If
      there are no objections, welcome aboard!</para>

      <informalfigure>
        <mediaobject>
          <imageobject>
            <imagedata fileref="illustrations/Image21.png" width="100%"/>
          </imageobject>
        </mediaobject>
      </informalfigure>
    </section>

    <section>
      <title><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#46818D" font="sansserif" -->Form
      sub-circles or roles?</title>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->As
      your circle is launching, this booklet can predict less and less what
      your group’s needs might be. This agenda item gives you a chance to be
      intentional on whether you would like to expand your group into
      subgroups or not. Even if you decide to stay as one group, for now, hear
      me out because you might need it for the future.</para>

      <section>
        <title><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#808080" -->Sub-circles</title>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->The
        idea of circles is to have a perfect fit between people who care about
        a domain and the circle. If you have noticed that different people
        have energy in different domains, it might be a good idea to form
        sub-groups. We don’t want that, in a group of eight, three people love
        to talk about something that doesn’t interest the other five. In that
        case, everyone is much better off if those three people form a
        sub-group on their sub-topic. Said in another way, we want to create
        circles where most of the agenda items are relevant for <emphasis
        role="from-text">all</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->
        people in the circle. But how do you do that well?</para>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Remember
        your group’s aim? As you grow, that overall aim will turn into the
        organization’s aim. Sub-circles will take on sub-sets of that aim as
        their sub-circle aim.</para>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->The
        same is true for the domain. If you form a sub-circle, then it is an
        <emphasis role="bold">empowered</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->
        sub-circle. The members of the <emphasis
        role="from-text">sub-circle</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->
        then hold the <emphasis role="bold">authority and
        responsibility</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->
        for that sub-domain, and <emphasis role="from-text">not</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->
        your original, general circle anymore. Therefore, clarify what the
        sub-circle is in charge of (= domain) that <emphasis
        role="from-text">you don’t</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->
        do anymore.</para>

        <informaltable>
          <!--Warning: passing through `tabular` element: -->

          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" yoffset="-0.9pt" --><mediaobject>
                  <imageobject>
                    <imagedata fileref="illustrations/Image22.png"
                               width="100%"/>
                  </imageobject>
                </mediaobject></td>

              <td><!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><emphasis
              role="bold">Circle domain:<!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: font="medium" --></emphasis>
              <!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: class="ltx_ulem_sout" color="#808080" fontsize="90%" -->fundraising
              and<!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#808080" fontsize="90%" -->
              funding awards for young transgender and gender-nonconforming
              artists <!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><emphasis
              role="bold">Sub-circle domain:<!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: font="medium" --></emphasis>
              <!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#808080" fontsize="90%" -->fundraising</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </informaltable>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->In
        this example, suppose you are a group that has as its aim <emphasis
        role="from-text">fundraising and funding awards for young transgender
        and gender-nonconforming artists in Western
        Massachusetts</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->.
        In that case, you might want to form a sub-circle that takes care of
        fundraising, while picking award winners might still remains in the
        founding circle.</para>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Now
        that we know that, here’s the checklist. To form a successful,
        semi-autonomous sub-circle, you pass on:<itemizedlist>
            <listitem>
              <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->that
              part of the aim</para>
            </listitem>

            <listitem>
              <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->that
              part of the domain</para>
            </listitem>

            <listitem>
              <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->plan
              for membership</para>
            </listitem>

            <listitem>
              <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->select
              a leader to link</para>
            </listitem>
          </itemizedlist><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->The
        full formation of the sub-circle might have to wait. The selections
        and launching of those sub-circles can happen in subsequent meetings –
        more on forming subcircles in Chapter <xref
        linkend="formingsubcircles"/><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->
        on page <xref linkend="formingsubcircles"/><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->.
        But in this meeting, you start the conversation.</para>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->To
        do so, ask the group whether they see topics that might be put into a
        sub-circle. Ideally, you do this in a round or two. After you have
        heard everyone, you harvest the ideas that emerged. The facilitator
        might make a proposal (or asks someone to make a proposal), for
        example, “I propose that we form a sub-circle on the topic XY.” You
        can then put that circle in place right away by defining aim, domain,
        leader, and a plan on how to populate the circle, or you put “forming
        XY circle” onto your backlog and continue at a future meeting.</para>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->How
        does one populate a new circle with new members? You can use the
        selection process very similar to what you have already done: everyone
        nominates two or three people for the circle; you do a change round
        and then have a proposal and find consent.</para>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->You
        might choose sub-circle members from among your circle members, or you
        might add ‘new’ people from outside the young organization. (My
        favorite option is to pick 2-3 members for the new circle to form it
        and then ask the sub-circle to add people of their own choosing. That
        way, we give them a solid start but also a lot of choice. That
        sub-circle can add people outside the circle in the same way again as
        described on page <xref linkend="newmembers"/><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->.)</para>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->In
        sociocracy, we use linking to get a good flow of information between
        the circles. The leader of the (sub-)circle serves as ‘top-down’ link
        for the new sub-circle.</para>

        <informaltable>
          <!--Warning: passing through `tabular` element: -->

          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" yoffset="-0.9pt" --><mediaobject>
                  <imageobject>
                    <imagedata fileref="illustrations/Image24.png"
                               width="100%"/>
                  </imageobject>
                </mediaobject></td>

              <td><!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->
              <!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><emphasis
              role="bold">Top-down link to form the circle (leader)<!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: font="medium" --></emphasis>
              <!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><emphasis
              role="bold">Bottom-up link to securely link the circle
              (delegate)</emphasis></td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </informaltable>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Once
        the new sub-circle circle is up and running, they will confirm that
        leader by consent (or propose someone else). They will also select a
        different person as a delegate who will be/stay a member of the
        original circle. With two people being part of both circles, the two
        circles are now securely attached and information can flow.</para>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->You
        have created an organism that can now grow limbs – like a cell that is
        forming new cells!</para>
      </section>

      <section>
        <title><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#808080" -->Roles</title>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->What
        do you do if there is only one person who is interested in working on
        a topic? In that case, you don’t form a whole circle, but you form an
        operational role. One individual can fill several roles, and they can
        fill them for a while until someone else fills that role – just like a
        hat that one person wears for a certain time frame.</para>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->In
        this meeting, identify potential roles and either put it on the
        backlog, or make sure someone writes role descriptions to approve at a
        future meeting. You will then either propose someone directly (if
        there’s really only one realistic candidate), or you fill your newly
        defined role for a certain time frame using the selection
        process.</para>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Complete
        as much as possible during your meeting. Then add any open steps to
        your backlog to continue in a future meeting.</para>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->The
        work of identifying topics, interests, and energy, people, and gaps
        will remain the ongoing work of every circle for as long as the
        organization exists.</para>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->You
        have now created an organism that can add internal structure – maybe
        like a cell with organelles. You add as much internal differentiation
        as you choose to and find useful.</para>

        <informalfigure>
          <mediaobject>
            <imageobject>
              <imagedata fileref="illustrations/Image23.png" width="100%"/>
            </imageobject>
          </mediaobject>
        </informalfigure>
      </section>
    </section>

    <section>
      <title><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#46818D" font="sansserif" -->Operationalize
      priority item #1</title>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Now
      how do you turn topics into outcomes?</para>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->In
      general, work is done outside of meetings. Meetings help us create
      <emphasis role="from-text">just enough</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->
      clarity and structure so that the work can happen with ease and
      alignment. In my experience, it’s specificity that unleashes energy to
      act. Creating structure and clarity can mean defining <emphasis
      role="from-text">how</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->
      we do things (workflow or policy agreements) or who does them
      (roles).</para>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Maybe
      a proposal “falls” out of the brainstorming session. In that case,
      simply phrase the idea as a proposal and go through the consent process
      (present the proposal/clarifying questions, quick reaction round,
      consent).</para>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->While
      forward motion is great, sometimes, it might be that you just bounce
      ideas in reaction rounds and don’t get there within one meeting.
      Sometimes topics need to marinate a little. That’s ok. Just bring them
      back in the future.</para>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Yet,
      if you’re ready to act but you don’t quite have enough specificity and
      clarity to move forward, below is a robust process that you can use to
      generate a specific proposal.</para>

      <section>
        <title><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#808080" -->Needs
        statement (optional)</title>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->What
        is the issue you are trying to solve? If the problem you are trying to
        solve is crystal clear to everyone, do the short version.</para>

        <para><emphasis role="bold">Short version:</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->
        Simply describe the need in a short statement and ask if people are on
        the same page in describing the need. A <emphasis
        role="from-text">needs statement</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->
        might sound like this: “We need to secure funding to support
        transgender and gender-nonconforming artists in the region.”</para>

        <para><emphasis role="bold">Longer version:</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->
        If you would like to explore more, you follow the process below. You
        can do each in rounds, with one or two rounds per step.<itemizedlist>
            <listitem>
              <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Identify
              what information there is to know about the problem. Share
              whatever context should be known to everyone.</para>
            </listitem>

            <listitem>
              <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->What
              are needs at play here? Who is affected?</para>
            </listitem>

            <listitem>
              <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Summarize.
              The facilitator describes (or asks someone to) the need in one
              or more sentences and checks whether everyone agrees with that
              <emphasis role="from-text">needs statement</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->.</para>
            </listitem>
          </itemizedlist><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->(More
        details can be found in the manual <emphasis role="from-text">Many
        Voices One Song</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->,
        section 3.3.2: The three phases of policy process.)</para>
      </section>

      <section>
        <title><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#808080" -->Co-creating
        a proposal</title>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->To
        generate a proposal, answer these questions, starting with the column
        on the left, then the middle, and then ask one person to synthesize
        their ideas from column two into a proposal.</para>

        <informaltable>
          <!--Warning: passing through `tabular` element: -->

          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->darkerteal
              <emphasis role="bold">Dimensions</emphasis></td>

              <td><!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><emphasis
              role="bold">Proposal ideas</emphasis></td>

              <td><!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><emphasis
              role="bold">Synthesize</emphasis></td>
            </tr>

            <tr>
              <td><!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->lightteal
              What areas do we need to consider? <!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->(nouns/questions)</td>

              <td><!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->On
              those areas, what are <!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->specific<!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->
              ideas? <!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->(<emphasis
              role="from-text">I think we should</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->
              statements)</td>

              <td><!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Formulate
              one proposal from the ideas gathered</td>
            </tr>

            <tr>
              <td><!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->verylightgrey
                <!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" width="0.0pt" -->•<!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->  …
              <!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->•
              <!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->…
              <!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->•
              <!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->…</td>

              <td><!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->  <!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" width="0.0pt" -->•<!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->  …
              <!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->•
              <!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->…
              <!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->•
              <!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->…</td>

              <td><!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->  <!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" width="0.0pt" -->•<!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->  …
              <!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->•
              <!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->…
              <!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->•
              <!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->…</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </informaltable>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->See
        what this could look like for the fundraising question.</para>

        <informaltable>
          <!--Warning: passing through `tabular` element: -->

          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->darkerteal
              <emphasis role="bold">Dimensions</emphasis></td>

              <td><!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><emphasis
              role="bold">Proposal ideas</emphasis></td>

              <td><!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><emphasis
              role="bold">Synthesize</emphasis></td>
            </tr>

            <tr>
              <td><!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->verylightgrey
                <!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" width="0.0pt" -->•<!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->  fundraising?
              <!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->•
              <!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->timeline
              <!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->•
              <!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->big/small
              donors <!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->•
              <!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->hire
              someone? <!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->•
              <!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->grant
              writing? <!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->•
              <!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->sponsors?
              <!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->•
              <!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->other
              events?</td>

              <td><!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->For
              3 months, pursue grants and fundraising, then evaluate. <!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Not
              hire for now <!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Make
              a list of potential organizational donors <!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Participate
              in giving day</td>

              <td><!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->  <!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" width="0.0pt" -->•<!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->  …</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </informaltable>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->In
        this case, the proposal ideas in the second column can be put together
        into a proposal. It will look like magic how quickly you got there!
        For example, the proposal here could sound like this:</para>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#46818D" fontsize="90%" -->“We
        will engage in three volunteer-based fundraising activities: (a) make
        a list of potential organizational donors and reach out, (b)
        participate in Giving Day event, and (c) pursue other grants. Term: 3
        months.”<!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" --></para>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->This
        proposal will then be approved or amended using the consent process in
        the whole circle.</para>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->If
        the proposal ideas don’t converge and align as neatly (or, if some
        ideas are even contradicting each other), appoint a person or a small
        team to synthesize the ideas into a proposal, which, again, will be
        approved or amended in the whole circle.</para>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Just
        like in the previous agenda item, there is no expectation of
        completing today. Maybe you make the lists in the first column
        (dimensions) for each of your three priority agenda items. Maybe you
        complete one and start the others. It’s your choice – together. For
        time and topic management, the facilitator can make a proposal, for
        example: “I propose we work on this topic for another 10 minutes and
        then we start the process for the other two items. Is there anyone who
        can’t work with that?” That way, you can get several things underway
        at the same time.</para>
      </section>
    </section>

    <section>
      <title><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#46818D" font="sansserif" -->Operationalize
      priority item #2 and #3</title>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->In
      the previous agenda items, you have experienced the process that will
      now apply to all new items – and carry on forever. You will surface new
      issues, understand them, explore what needs to be done, come up with a
      proposal, make decisions, and carry them out. Simply continue for as
      long as the organization exists.</para>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->If
      you breeze through everything, you might have proposal ideas on all
      three priority items right away. Consent and start experimenting!</para>
    </section>

    <section>
      <title><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#46818D" font="sansserif" -->Review
      the process so far</title>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->To
      adjust to an ever-changing context, any group needs to be resilient. A
      key feature of resilient groups is to evaluate what they are doing and
      adapt if needed. To get into that habit, let’s do a quick evaluation of
      processes so far.</para>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Do
      one round where people can reflect on how the group has been doing, for
      example, on the following topics:<itemizedlist>
          <listitem>
            <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Meeting
            format and facilitation, incl. time management</para>
          </listitem>

          <listitem>
            <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Sense
            of connection</para>
          </listitem>

          <listitem>
            <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Pace
            and progress</para>
          </listitem>

          <listitem>
            <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->(any
            other topic)</para>
          </listitem>
        </itemizedlist></para>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->If
      issues surface that should be addressed, either address them right away
      or put them on your backlog. For example, if someone hasn’t received
      emails because their address was inaccurate, fix that immediately. If
      someone is expressing discomfort with something more general – like
      gender dynamics in the group – put it on the backlog and make time for
      it at a future meeting.</para>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Thank
      everyone for their input, and go to the next item. Do not get dragged
      into a lengthy discussion here. As a circle, we operate best when we do
      not always go for instant gratification. The urgent (or urgent-feeling)
      should not trump the important, and you have consented to an agenda that
      now requires your attention.</para>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->If
      someone drops a bombshell in the evaluation and the meeting cannot
      continue, renegotiate the agenda and find consent again.</para>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Warning:
      you have to make sure there is a balance between building structure
      (e.g., behavior code, or how we divide up the money if we ever make any)
      and operations. Don’t jump into doing when key agreements need to be
      made first. But also don’t get lost in the process when you could also
      launch pilot projects. The backlog is a great tool to say yes to topics
      without commitment to address them right away.</para>
    </section>

    <section>
      <title><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#46818D" font="sansserif" -->Update
      the backlog</title>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Now
      that you’ve worked on your first backlog items make sure to update what
      your backlog says. For example, the question of “how might we secure
      funding” now gets updated into “make a decision on the funding proposal”
      if that’s what you worked on.</para>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Add
      all additional ideas and issues, as well as review dates onto the
      backlog for the future.</para>

      <informalfigure>
        <mediaobject>
          <imageobject>
            <imagedata fileref="illustrations/Image25.png" width="100%"/>
          </imageobject>
        </mediaobject>
      </informalfigure>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Now
      you simply do this forever! The backlog will be the thread connecting
      your individual meetings to make sure you are accountable to your own
      decisions and keep the group focused and coherent.</para>
    </section>

    <section>
      <title><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#46818D" font="sansserif" -->Check-out</title>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->As
      usual, end the meeting with a check-out. I am sure you are exhausted.
      That was (again!) a lot of ground covered today!</para>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Make
      it a habit to become more and more specific and honest in your meeting
      evaluations. If you don’t name them, sub-optimal habits or processes
      will persist. Name them early, name them gracefully, and put them on the
      backlog for future problem-solving.</para>
    </section>

