  <chapter>
    <title><emphasis role="bold">The building blocks of
    self-governance</emphasis></title>

    <section>
      <title><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#46818D" font="sansserif" -->Structure,
      content, review</title>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->As
      a group, you now have all the pieces you need:</para>

      <para><itemizedlist>
          <listitem>
            <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Your
            backlog holds all open topics.</para>
          </listitem>

          <listitem>
            <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Address
            topics by co-creating and consenting proposals.</para>
          </listitem>

          <listitem>
            <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Differentiate
            and decentralize with roles and sub-circles with aims and domains,
            membership, links, and delegate.</para>
          </listitem>

          <listitem>
            <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->With
            the selection process, select people into roles/circles and pick
            topics to prioritize.</para>
          </listitem>

          <listitem>
            <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->As
            needed, review your processes and surface new topics to improve
            them over time.</para>
          </listitem>
        </itemizedlist><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->All
      the rest is just refinement and replication. The building blocks stay
      the same. Now you can do anything you can imagine!</para>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Ideally,
      the facilitator and leader prepare the agenda proposal ahead of time.
      But even if there’s no agenda prepared, with these building blocks in
      place, you can make an <emphasis role="from-text">instant
      agenda</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->
      fast:<itemizedlist>
          <listitem>
            <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Do
            a round where people say they need to talk about (and whether
            their proposed item is a report, exploration, or a
            decision).</para>
          </listitem>

          <listitem>
            <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->The
            facilitator turns the suggestions into a proposal and works
            towards consent.</para>
          </listitem>

          <listitem>
            <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Make
            sure to add all extra topics onto the backlog for future
            meetings.</para>
          </listitem>
        </itemizedlist></para>
    </section>

    <section xml:id="formingsubcircles">
      <title><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#46818D" font="sansserif" -->How
      to start a sub-circle</title>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Growth
      in a decentralized, self-governed organization doesn’t happen by growing
      bigger groups. It happens by growing more circles, just like an organism
      doesn’t grow by having one big cell but by having <emphasis
      role="from-text">many</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->
      cells. Similarly, as cells in an organism are formed by another cell for
      a certain purpose and location, sub-circles are formed by circles for a
      certain purpose: the aim. As stated above, sub-circles receive the aim
      as well as their domain from their sub-circle. The parent circle also
      puts a plan in place on how to populate the new sub-circle intentionally
      and makes sure there’s clarity on how the new sub-circle and the forming
      circle are linked.</para>

      <section>
        <title><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#808080" -->A
        proposal to form a sub-circle</title>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Let’s
        look at what a proposal to form a sub-circle could look like to give
        you a good start. For our scenario, let’s imagine this is a group of 6
        that is meeting for the 5th time following this process. They know
        their aim, and they have all the roles clear, consent as
        decision-making, rounds for talking, they defined their circle
        membership by consent, and they know each other. As an example, let’s
        say this group has as its aim to run an organic and fair-trade tea
        store in Cambridge. While the original circle is talking about all
        aspects of this new enterprise (defining their audience, choice, and
        testing of products, researching suppliers, etc.), they also want to
        start looking for a physical location of their store. Early on, they
        had identified <emphasis role="from-text">physical
        location?</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->
        as an open topic and put it on their backlog. In the prioritization,
        this topic ended up pretty high, so now it’s on the agenda.</para>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->In
        talking about the topic, they notice that only some of the 6 have
        strong opinions and interests in this topic while others have more
        energy around other topics. The opinion forms that this topic best be
        held by a sub-set of the group because discussing it could easily take
        up all the available time, and they want the process to start in
        parallel to planning all the other aspects of the store. So they
        decide to form a sub-circle.</para>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Here’s
        the checklist for forming a sub-circle from earlier.<itemizedlist>
            <listitem>
              <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Define
              the aim of the sub-circle</para>
            </listitem>

            <listitem>
              <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Define
              the domain of the domain</para>
            </listitem>

            <listitem>
              <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Define
              a plan for membership</para>
            </listitem>

            <listitem>
              <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Select
              a leader for linking (and set the expectation that a delegate be
              selected by the new circle as a backlink)</para>
            </listitem>
          </itemizedlist></para>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->The
        group might do rounds in trying to answer these questions until
        they’ve pieced together a proposal: <!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" --></para>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#46818D" fontsize="90%" -->Proposal
        to form a Location Search Circle.<itemizedlist>
            <listitem>
              <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#46818D" fontsize="90%" -->Aim:
              identifying a suitable location for the store.</para>
            </listitem>

            <listitem>
              <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#46818D" fontsize="90%" -->Domain:
              store location</para>
            </listitem>

            <listitem>
              <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#46818D" fontsize="90%" -->Membership:
              Jane and Tahiana as members for now, encouraging them to find
              more people as needed.</para>
            </listitem>
          </itemizedlist></para>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->They
        consent to this proposal and enter a selection process to select a
        leader for this circle. Knowing that both of them are well-suited,
        they still settle for Tahiana as the leader for this circle because
        she has some previous experience. Jane mentions a friend of hers that
        had offered a few ideas on suitable locations for the store, and they
        make plans to invite that friend as a new circle member.</para>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Later
        on, this circle might select Jane or the new person as a delegate to
        join the parent circle. It is not unusual to have founders like Jane –
        who is already a member of the parent circle for now – in several
        linking roles of different circles while the group is still small. As
        the organization and the sub-circles mature, non-founders will be in
        new positions more and more. If we spread too fast, our organization
        might become incoherent and disconnected – grow at a pace that feels
        refreshing but safe.</para>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Notice
        that in the domain, it says “store location”. If this is approved as
        the domain as is, the sub-circle will be empowered to <emphasis
        role="from-text">choose</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->
        the store location. If this is not what the parent circle wants, it
        would need to be changed accordingly, for example, to “making a
        recommendation for a store location (to be approved by the parent
        circle)”. Ideally, sub-circles are empowered to make decisions –
        that’s what decentralized decision making is all about. It is a very
        common point of tension and misunderstandings, so be sure to be clear
        exactly what authority you give the sub-circle!</para>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->If
        you would like to see more details and examples for circle structure
        and linking, please refer to the sociocracy manual <emphasis
        role="from-text">Many Voices One Song</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->,
        Chapter 2: Organizational Structure.</para>
      </section>

      <section>
        <title><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#808080" -->Passing
        on the DNA</title>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->In
        the example of the tea store, the focus was on the mechanics of
        proposing and populating a sub-circle. In addition to the pure
        mechanics, we need to talk about culture. You want your organism to
        grow without turning into a hierarchical, centralized system. To
        achieve that, each of the parts needs to carry the same DNA as the
        original circle. By that, I mean: commitment to hearing all voices in
        consent and in rounds, decentralized authority based on good and
        transparent information flow through linking and trust.</para>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Given
        that we are operating in a culture where these values and principles
        are not the default in organizations, the risk is that we revert to
        the mainstream culture over time. In my experience, sub-circles often
        water down the standards until the system becomes unworkable. The only
        ways to prevent that are to<itemizedlist>
            <listitem>
              <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->set
              expectations insist that they are kept</para>
            </listitem>

            <listitem>
              <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->give
              support in meeting those expectations</para>
            </listitem>
          </itemizedlist><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->If
        you care about the tools and values in your original circle, make sure
        they are passed on to all sub-circles.</para>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Let’s
        play with another example for illustration. Let us imagine a group
        that has formed to achieve the aim of publishing a magazine for
        care-takers of children with learning challenges. Let’s imagine this
        organization is already somewhat formed (they have several functional
        circles for different aspects of their project), but now they want to
        form local chapters in different counties to report on local resources
        for their audience. They decide to form circles in 3 different
        counties. How can they make sure those county circles are aligned in
        their culture and values?</para>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->In
        my experience, the best way to pass on tools and the inclusive culture
        by committing to practices and living them. In every sub-circle, you
        need to have at least <emphasis role="from-text">one</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->
        person who can model by example and support the oncoming members in
        acquiring the skills and processes.</para>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->When
        forming a sub-circle, you will have at least one person (the selected
        leader) that has been through several meetings based on
        self-organization with tools from sociocracy. If this person is
        willing and able, they can be the <emphasis
        role="from-text">sociocracy guide</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->,
        or <emphasis role="from-text">self-organization guide</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->
        for the sub-circle. (If the leader is not willing and able, make an
        alternative plan. For example, you could have a second person in the
        sub-circle hold that role, at least temporarily, or make an effort to
        train one of the sub-circle members to be that person.)</para>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->The
        next section spells out the first meeting(s) of the sub-circle.</para>
      </section>

      <section>
        <title><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#808080" -->The
        first sub-circle meeting</title>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->The
        first meeting of a sub-circle is very similar to the founding meeting.
        It’s just a little bit easier because a few parameters are set.
        Excitingly, the templates you used to form the original circle can
        also be used for each sub-circle. By default, the leader will
        facilitate until roles are set or appoint a facilitator following this
        process.</para>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Looking
        back at the template for meeting #1, here’s how each agenda item
        translates.<itemizedlist>
            <listitem>
              <para><emphasis role="bold">Commitment to
              rounds/consent.</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->
              Each circle needs to commit to the DNA of the organization, so
              it makes sense to commit to rounds and consent as a way to hear
              everyone in each circle.</para>
            </listitem>

            <listitem>
              <para><emphasis role="bold">Decision about the
              aim/domain.</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->
              There is an aim put in place by the parent circle which is very
              similar to the proposed aim that the convener put in place as
              the original invitation. The people who are meeting as a
              sub-circle for the first time need to <emphasis
              role="bold">accept and affirm that aim and domain as
              theirs</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->.
              This step will ensure that the sub-circle members understand how
              they fit into the overall organization and what their
              authorities and responsibilities are.</para>

              <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Note:
              the domain of the original circle was “everything”. Now with at
              least two circles in the mix, being clear about each other’s
              domains becomes more important. Be sure to have clarity on what
              the parent circle will not be in charge of anymore. Having that
              clarity will help the sub-circle become empowered, responsible
              and motivated!</para>
            </listitem>

            <listitem>
              <para><emphasis role="bold">Experience with regard to the
              aim.</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->
              You might know each other already, but do you know about each
              other’s experience on this sub-aim? This might be easy and
              brief, but it might make sense to do. For example, you might
              know each other from an activist context, but if you are forming
              a Website Circle–do you know each other’s website expertise and
              experience?</para>
            </listitem>

            <listitem>
              <para><emphasis role="bold">Getting to know each
              other.</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->
              If you have new members, definitely spend some time getting to
              know each other. If you already know each other, skip this
              step.</para>
            </listitem>

            <listitem>
              <para><emphasis role="bold">Defining the founding
              members.</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->
              Consent to yourselves and each other’s sub-circle membership to
              formally form the circle. This is a matter of one minute if
              everything is clear. If it’s not clear – for example, because
              one person isn’t sure whether they have time to contribute in
              the sub-circle – talk about it now!</para>
            </listitem>

            <listitem>
              <para><emphasis role="bold">Next meeting.</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->
              When are you meeting next? How often do you think your
              sub-circle should meet?</para>
            </listitem>
          </itemizedlist></para>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Depending
        on how simple the situation is, the template for meeting #1 might be
        only the first few minutes of the first meeting, and you will move on
        to the next topics from template #2. Yet, especially if there are a
        lot of new people, do not rush the beginning. Lack of clarity on the
        overall aim will catch up with you later. Lack of clarity around
        process or domains will likely bite you as well!</para>

        <informalfigure>
          <mediaobject>
            <imageobject>
              <imagedata fileref="illustrations/Image26.png" width="100%"/>
            </imageobject>
          </mediaobject>
        </informalfigure>
      </section>

      <section xml:id="topics">
        <title><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#808080" -->Subsequent
        sub-circle meetings</title>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->How
        do the agenda items from meeting template #2 and #3 apply to a
        sub-circle instead of a founding circle?</para>

        <para><itemizedlist>
            <listitem>
              <para><emphasis role="bold">Selecting roles.</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->
              This agenda item applies in the same way as in a founding
              circle. You have a leader (selected by the parent circle), but
              you need to confirm that leader by consent. Sometimes the person
              convening the sub-circle doesn’t want to be leader beyond
              forming the circle. In that case, you simply add the leader role
              to the roles you need to select in a selection process.</para>

              <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->What’s
              different this time is that you also need to select a delegate.
              (Unlike the founding circle, you have a parent circle to link
              to!) That means you are selecting a facilitator, secretary,
              delegate, and maybe a (new) leader.</para>

              <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Since
              I am chronically concerned about watered-down commitments around
              governance, <emphasis role="from-text">I’d</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->
              make sure that the person who is selected facilitator either is
              the most sociocratically-experienced person in the room or ask
              them to follow the processes laid out here. I can only offer
              this template – but I also know it only becomes lived experience
              if you choose to <emphasis role="from-text">use</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->
              it.</para>

              <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Here’s
              another comment from having seen many of these processes. To
              become operational as fast as possible, it might seem to take a
              long time to select roles for the sub-circle. If you are itching
              to get going, just have the leader make a proposal who could
              fill which role, put a short term on it (!), and then approve by
              consent. In doing so, you are missing out on being more
              intentional and getting to know each other better, and I
              <emphasis role="from-text">definitely don’t</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->
              recommend skipping full selection processes forever. But there’s
              a lot to say for starting lean, and it might make sense to jump
              into action fast while committing to do the full process once
              the first term is up. Setting terms on quick-and-dirty decisions
              is a great strategy of being fast but intentional. We don’t need
              to figure everything out right away before we can even do a
              first step. Instead, we experiment and commit to a timeline of
              when we will add more groundwork and reflection.</para>
            </listitem>

            <listitem>
              <para><emphasis role="bold">Infrastructure and
              communication.</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->
              This agenda item from meeting #2 may or may not apply. You might
              simply decide to use the same communication system that the
              parent circle is using. Or maybe you want your own. If things
              are obvious, make a proposal, consent, and move on. If they are
              not obvious, take some time to talk.</para>
            </listitem>

            <listitem>
              <para><emphasis role="bold">Gather items for the
              backlog.</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->
              This is an excellent practice for any new circle. Gathering
              topics for later discussion or decision will help the circle get
              to know each other’s priorities and understand what the circle’s
              scope (domain) is in each other’s perception. Compiling the list
              of future agenda items, therefore, is a good tool for alignment,
              hearing everyone, and making sure we can operate soon and with
              alignment to the whole.</para>
            </listitem>

            <listitem>
              <para><emphasis role="bold">Prioritize the
              backlog.</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->
              Applies just like in the original circle.</para>
            </listitem>

            <listitem>
              <para><emphasis role="bold">Add new members? Select new
              members</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->.
              Applies just like in the original circle.</para>
            </listitem>
          </itemizedlist></para>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->And
        how about the agenda items from meeting #3? Let’s keep this short:
        they all apply. Simply go back to Chapter <xref
        linkend="meeting3"/><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->
        on page <xref linkend="meeting3"/><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->.</para>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->In
        my experience, a sub-circle can be kick-started within one meeting if
        things are easy and people are experienced. Instead of looking at the
        templates for the meetings one by one, look at the order of topics.
        They all build on each other. Go through them step by step while
        holding a good balance of diligence, pace, and pragmatism. Monitoring
        your own pace is a skill not unique to starting a self-governed
        organization, but it’s a skillset needed in all phases of your
        evolution as an organization. Here’s what I do: I follow common sense
        and go as fast as I think we <emphasis
        role="from-text">can</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->
        go. Then I slow it down just 10%. Why? Because it’s easy to be
        oblivious and miss pieces or concerns if you go too fast. Having to
        backtrack when we made a mess costs time. Also, I never compromise on
        consent – it’s our safety net to make sure all voices are ultimately
        heard.</para>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->For
        reference, see the below list of items to form a sub-circle in the
        most organic order. Topics #1-10 set up the infrastructure of the
        circle. You can, of course, revisit and improve those points
        later.</para>

        <informaltable>
          <!--Warning: passing through `tabular` element: -->

          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->lightteal
              <!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" font="sansserif" fontsize="90%" -->#1</td>

              <td><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Commitment
              to rounds/consent</td>
            </tr>

            <tr>
              <td><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->lightteal
              <!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" font="sansserif" fontsize="90%" -->#2</td>

              <td><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Decision
              about the aim</td>
            </tr>

            <tr>
              <td><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->lightteal
              <!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" font="sansserif" fontsize="90%" -->#3</td>

              <td><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Experience
              with regard to the aim</td>
            </tr>

            <tr>
              <td><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->lightteal
              <!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" font="sansserif" fontsize="90%" -->#4</td>

              <td><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Getting
              to know each other</td>
            </tr>

            <tr>
              <td><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->lightteal
              <!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" font="sansserif" fontsize="90%" -->#5</td>

              <td><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Decision
              founding membership</td>
            </tr>

            <tr>
              <td><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->lightteal
              <!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" font="sansserif" fontsize="90%" -->#6</td>

              <td><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Next
              meeting/meeting frequency</td>
            </tr>

            <tr>
              <td><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->lightteal
              <!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" font="sansserif" fontsize="90%" -->#7</td>

              <td><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Selecting
              roles</td>
            </tr>

            <tr>
              <td><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->lightteal
              <!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" font="sansserif" fontsize="90%" -->#8</td>

              <td><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Infrastructure
              &amp; communication</td>
            </tr>

            <tr>
              <td><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->lightteal
              <!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" font="sansserif" fontsize="90%" -->#9</td>

              <td><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Gather
              items for the backlog &amp; prioritize</td>
            </tr>

            <tr>
              <td><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->lightteal
              <!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" font="sansserif" fontsize="90%" -->#10</td>

              <td><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Add
              new members? | select/integrate new members</td>
            </tr>

            <tr>
              <td><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->darkerteal
              <!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" font="sansserif" fontsize="90%" -->#11</td>

              <td><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Address
              backlog items</td>
            </tr>

            <tr>
              <td><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->darkerteal
              <!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" font="sansserif" fontsize="90%" -->#12</td>

              <td><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Review
              processes and policies</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </informaltable>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Then
        we enter maintenance mode. At the end of each meeting and whenever
        issues arise, we gather items for the backlog. As part of that, topics
        #11 and #12 of addressing backlog items (making decisions and
        implementing them) and evaluating any decisions we have made
        (including role performance, policy reviews, etc.) become an ongoing
        practice as needed or at the end of a term. Forming new sub-circles
        and roles, selecting people into roles or adding new members are now
        just part of the backlog items that each circle will address with the
        regular tools.</para>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->To
        plan a sub-circle meeting, simply wrap the meeting structure around as
        many agenda items as you think you will cover, and you’re good to
        go!</para>

        <informaltable>
          <!--Warning: passing through `tabular` element: -->

          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->lightgray
              <!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" font="sansserif" fontsize="90%" -->min</td>

              <td><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" font="sansserif" fontsize="90%" -->Phase</td>

              <td><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" font="sansserif" fontsize="90%" -->Topics</td>
            </tr>

            <tr>
              <td><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->verylightgrey
              <!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" font="sansserif" fontsize="90%" -->5</td>

              <td><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" font="sansserif" fontsize="90%" -->Opening</td>

              <td><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" font="sansserif" fontsize="90%" -->Check-in</td>
            </tr>

            <tr>
              <td><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" font="sansserif" fontsize="90%" -->3</td>

              <td/>

              <td><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" font="sansserif" fontsize="90%" -->ADMIN</td>
            </tr>

            <tr>
              <td><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->verylightgrey
              <!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" font="sansserif" fontsize="90%" -->2</td>

              <td><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" font="sansserif" fontsize="90%" -->Content</td>

              <td><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" font="sansserif" fontsize="90%" -->Consent
              to agenda</td>
            </tr>

            <tr>
              <td><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->darkerteal
              x</td>

              <td/>

              <td><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" font="sansserif" fontsize="90%" -->Topics</td>
            </tr>

            <tr>
              <td><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" font="sansserif" fontsize="90%" -->1</td>

              <td/>

              <td><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" font="sansserif" fontsize="90%" -->Update
              backlog</td>
            </tr>

            <tr>
              <td><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->verylightgrey
              <!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" font="sansserif" fontsize="90%" -->4</td>

              <td><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" font="sansserif" fontsize="90%" -->Closing</td>

              <td><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" font="sansserif" fontsize="90%" -->Check-out</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </informaltable>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->To
        improve your practice, we recommend categorizing your agenda items
        into these categories:<itemizedlist>
            <listitem>
              <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Reports:
              one or more people in the circle have the information they want
              or need to pass on to the other circle members.</para>
            </listitem>

            <listitem>
              <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Explorations:
              one or more people in the circle have input and would like you
              to gather ideas or feedback from the circle. In that case, make
              sure the prompt or question is understood well, and then gather
              the input in rounds. This is also a good format to brainstorm
              etc.</para>
            </listitem>

            <listitem>
              <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Decisions:
              either generate a proposal or have a proposal ready. Make sure
              everyone understands the proposal and gets a chance to react.
              Then you make a decision.</para>
            </listitem>
          </itemizedlist><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->It
        is incredibly helpful to know which of these desired outcomes is
        expected in a meeting. It’s a helpful practice to add an <emphasis
        role="from-text">R</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->
        (for report), an <emphasis role="from-text">E</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->
        for exploration, or a <emphasis role="from-text">D</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->
        for decision to the agenda, so that everyone is on the same page and
        knows what to expect.</para>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->I
        adjusted the time intervals to adjust to a small(er), experienced, and
        focused group. It’s the time frames I use for the circle meetings I
        facilitate. All the “overhead” sums up to about 15 minutes – a
        reasonable time frame to make sure the circle is well-connected as
        human beings, organized as a circle, is tracking items reliably, and
        adapts and learns over time. Well worth it!</para>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Here
        are two examples of what an agenda could look like:<!--Warning: passing through `tabular` element: -->
        <informaltable>
            <tbody>
              <tr>
                <td><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->lightgray
                <!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" font="sansserif" fontsize="90%" -->min</td>

                <td><!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" font="sansserif" fontsize="90%" -->Topics</td>

                <td><!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" font="sansserif" fontsize="90%" -->Desired
                Outcome</td>
              </tr>

              <tr>
