    <section>
      <title><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#46818D" font="sansserif" -->The
      inversion point to decentralization</title>

      <informalfigure>
        <mediaobject>
          <imageobject>
            <imagedata fileref="illustrations/Image27.png" width="100%"/>
          </imageobject>
        </mediaobject>
      </informalfigure>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Once
      you have started several sub-circles, there will be one important
      movement in your evolution, and we call it the <emphasis
      role="bold">inversion point</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->.
      It’s what needs to happen so we can grow as a decentralized
      organization.</para>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->In
      the beginning, your founding circle is (or was) the <emphasis
      role="from-text">everyone circle</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->.
      All original members are automatically part of that <emphasis
      role="from-text">everyone circle</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->,
      like a primordial soup of your organization.</para>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->As
      we form linked sub-circles and add new members (the teal dots), we might
      still have the expectation that the circle in the center is the
      <emphasis role="from-text">everyone circle</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->.
      You might even have invited the new members of sub-circles to show up at
      the <emphasis role="from-text">everyone circle</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->
      meetings. If you do that or continue to do that, this group will grow
      and grow in its center, instead of the circles.</para>

      <informalfigure>
        <mediaobject>
          <imageobject>
            <imagedata fileref="illustrations/Image28.png" width="100%"/>
          </imageobject>
        </mediaobject>
      </informalfigure>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Notice
      the two members in the middle who are not links from circles, pointed
      out by the orange arrows.</para>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Now
      we need an inversion. By a decision in the <emphasis
      role="from-text">everyone circle</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->,
      <emphasis role="bold">only leaders and delegates remain in the center
      circle</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->,
      which is now a General Circle to coordinate alignment between the
      circles to make sure we know and have a way to decide who decides what.
      Most decisions will now live in the circles, not in the center circle
      anymore. New members (in teal) will join specific circles and either
      contribute there or serve as links to the GC in addition to that.
      <emphasis role="bold">That’s when you turn from a centralized
      organization into a decentralized organization.</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->
      If you miss that moment, your group will centralize and form a
      hierarchy, fade away, or simply not grow.</para>

      <informalfigure>
        <mediaobject>
          <imageobject>
            <imagedata fileref="illustrations/Image29.png" width="100%"/>
          </imageobject>
        </mediaobject>
      </informalfigure>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->The
      non-links formerly in the GC have two options if we want to avoid people
      in work circles who have opinions but don’t do work.<orderedlist>
          <listitem>
            <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->They
            join another circle and attend the meetings there.</para>
          </listitem>

          <listitem>
            <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->They
            remain members of the organization (stay on the email list, etc.),
            but they are not part of any work circles. They might attend
            all-member meetings for input and connection (not for
            decision-making).</para>
          </listitem>
        </orderedlist><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->You
      can select one person in the General Circle (GC) as the leader of the
      General Circle. This helps create clarity on who is holding attention to
      the General Circle’s well-being. The leader might be one of the leaders
      and delegates, or an extra person.</para>
    </section>

    <section xml:id="network">
      <title><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#46818D" font="sansserif" -->Network
      &amp; community gatherings</title>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->After
      the inversion happens, decision-making is distributed. It no longer
      resides in the central <emphasis role="from-text">everyone
      circle</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->,
      and neither in the General Circle. Instead, each circle takes up their
      work.</para>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->For
      some initiatives, distributed decision making means that they miss the
      sense of the whole of being in the <emphasis role="from-text">everyone
      circle</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->.
      But this group can still continue! It’s just that <emphasis
      role="from-text">decisions</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->
      are made in the circles that hold the respective domains. Here are some
      useful purposes of all-member gatherings.</para>

      <para><itemizedlist>
          <listitem>
            <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->During
            all-member gatherings, circles can ask for feedback and
            reflections that they then take back into their circle work.
            Feedback is something very different from making decisions. The
            feedback becomes input for the circle’s decision, allowing the
            circle to decide based on that input and the circle’s own
            deliberation.</para>
          </listitem>

          <listitem>
            <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->The
            people in the all-member gatherings, or the wider network, can
            also learn together, tell each other their life stories, get
            sociocracy training, go for hikes together, eat lunch together,
            talk on forums, show up for Open Space sessions, invite a guest
            speaker, have cleaning parties, or take anti-racism workshops.
            These are all activities that can be done well in a large group,
            inform our work, and enhance our connection with each other. Plan
            something inviting and establish all-member or network gatherings
            that fit you. These gatherings can also be useful to recruit new
            circle members for the operational parts of your work! (For more
            context, see <emphasis role="from-text">Many Voices One
            Song</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->,
            Ch. 2.7.1: Gatherings, interest groups and communities of
            practice.)</para>
          </listitem>

          <listitem>
            <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Connecting
            with the vision of the organization is an excellent use of time
            for all-member meetings. Your organization vision and purpose are
            like a fountain of youth for your operations, for gaining
            perspective and aligning our thinking. Spend time talking,
            exploring, reflecting on the vision, and get refreshed and
            re-connected. If you do not have a declared mission statement yet,
            it might be a good idea to workshop it now. It will embed the
            <emphasis role="from-text">what</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->
            in the <emphasis role="from-text">why</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->
            of your work and connect you beyond your operations.</para>
          </listitem>
        </itemizedlist></para>
    </section>

    <section>
      <title><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#46818D" font="sansserif" -->Planning
      long term: the Mission Circle</title>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Over
      time, you will most likely notice that your organization is great at
      doing things in many different places, but it lacks vision and long-term
      planning. That’s when you add a Mission Circle.</para>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->The
      Mission Circle consists of some internal members and some external
      members – those are the people bringing fresh ideas into the
      organization and serving as a connection to the outside world. You form
      a Mission Circle in the same way you would form a sub-circle from the
      General Circle. You decide to form the sub-circle, define what you want
      it to do, select people from the inside and outside. (We wrote more
      examples on Mission Circles and who might serve on an MC in <emphasis
      role="from-text">Many Voices One Song</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->,
      Chapter 2.5.3.</para>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->In
      classic sociocratic thinking, the leader of the General Circle is seen
      as the “top-down” link from the Mission Circle, and the General Circle
      would add a second, “bottom-up” link from the General Circle to the
      Mission Circle. No matter how you think about the directions, the leader
      of the GC and one additional person will make sure the Mission Circle
      and General Circle are well-connected by having two people who are
      members of both circles.</para>

      <informalfigure>
        <mediaobject>
          <imageobject>
            <imagedata fileref="illustrations/Image30.png" width="100%"/>
          </imageobject>
        </mediaobject>
      </informalfigure>
    </section>

    <section>
      <title><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#46818D" font="sansserif" -->Additional
      tools: review processes</title>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->There
      are more processes to learn and refine what you do and how you do it.
      They are listed below. (For all other processes and refinements, please
      refer to our sociocracy manual, <emphasis role="from-text">Many Voices
      One Song</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->.)</para>

      <section>
        <title><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#808080" -->Policy
        review</title>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Every
        policy decision we make need to be reviewed to remain up to date and
        useful. Typically, we add a review date at the same time we approve
        the policy, for example after 4 weeks, 6 months or 2 years. To review
        a simple policy, follow three steps:</para>

        <informaltable>
          <!--Warning: passing through `tabular` element: -->

          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" yoffset="-0.9pt" --><mediaobject>
                  <imageobject>
                    <imagedata fileref="illustrations/Image31a.png"
                               width="100%"/>
                  </imageobject>
                </mediaobject></td>

              <td><!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><emphasis
              role="bold">Understand<!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: font="medium" -->
              Review the current policy and make sure everyone knows what it
              says</emphasis></td>
            </tr>

            <tr>
              <td><!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" yoffset="-0.9pt" --><mediaobject>
                  <imageobject>
                    <imagedata fileref="illustrations/Image31b.png"
                               width="100%"/>
                  </imageobject>
                </mediaobject></td>

              <td><!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><emphasis
              role="bold">Explore<!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: font="medium" -->
              Do a reaction round and see what people see that might need
              improvement.</emphasis></td>
            </tr>

            <tr>
              <td><!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" yoffset="-0.9pt" --><mediaobject>
                  <imageobject>
                    <imagedata fileref="illustrations/Image31c.png"
                               width="100%"/>
                  </imageobject>
                </mediaobject></td>

              <td><!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><emphasis
              role="bold">Decide<!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: font="medium" -->
              Propose an amended policy (with a new term) and seek
              consent.</emphasis></td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </informaltable>
      </section>

      <section>
        <title><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#808080" -->Circle
        review</title>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->A
        circle review is a way to check in on group dynamics and everyone’s
        well-being. Different from a performance review, in the circle review,
        <emphasis role="from-text">everyone</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->
        in the group gives feedback to <emphasis
        role="from-text">everyone</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->.
        Steps:<orderedlist>
            <listitem>
              <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Focus
              person #1:<orderedlist>
                  <listitem>
                    <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->The
                    first focus person talks about what they did well and what
                    they might want to improve.</para>
                  </listitem>

                  <listitem>
                    <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->In
                    a round, everyone responds to that focus person and gives
                    feedback on their performance.</para>
                  </listitem>

                  <listitem>
                    <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->The
                    focus person reflects out loud on the feedback
                    received.</para>
                  </listitem>
                </orderedlist></para>
            </listitem>

            <listitem>
              <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Shift
              to the next focus person and follow the steps (a) to (c).</para>
            </listitem>

            <listitem>
              <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Repeat
              until all circle members have had reflection time and have
              received feedback.</para>
            </listitem>
          </orderedlist></para>

        <informalfigure>
          <mediaobject>
            <imageobject>
              <imagedata fileref="illustrations/Image32.png" width="100%"/>
            </imageobject>
          </mediaobject>
        </informalfigure>
      </section>

      <section>
        <title><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#808080" -->Performance
        reviews</title>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Performance
        reviews allow giving detailed feedback to a person in a role. It can
        be several hours or sessions long, depending on how important it is to
        the circle. More details are in <emphasis role="from-text">Many Voices
        One Song</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->,
        Chapter 4.6 or in our online resources.<itemizedlist>
            <listitem>
              <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Understand
              the roles this person is filling</para>
            </listitem>

            <listitem>
              <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->What
              has this person done well? (Start and end with the focus
              person)</para>
            </listitem>

            <listitem>
              <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->What
              didn’t go so well? (Start and end with the focus person)</para>
            </listitem>

            <listitem>
              <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->What
              are the areas of potential improvements, and what are concrete
              ideas for improvement?</para>
            </listitem>

            <listitem>
              <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Write
              up the concrete ideas into a proposal and seek consent.</para>
            </listitem>
          </itemizedlist></para>
      </section>
    </section>

    <section xml:id="objections">
      <title><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#46818D" font="sansserif" -->Facilitation
      training</title>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->In
      a review, you might surface that you need more training. I highly
      recommend getting some facilitators trained and become an even more
      resourceful, leader-full group. It’s hard to overestimate how much good
      additional training can do. Good meetings smoothen out all the rest, and
      more training lets everyone participate with ease and shared
      responsibility.</para>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->The
      biggest points of improvement are skills of integrating objections, and
      experience on how to not get sidetracked in a meeting. That is outside
      of the scope of this booklet. We would like to point you to the articles
      and sample meeting recordings on our facilitation webpage.</para>

      <informalfigure>
        <mediaobject>
          <imageobject>
            <imagedata fileref="illustrations/Image33.png" width="100%"/>
          </imageobject>
        </mediaobject>
      </informalfigure>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->As
      an appetizer, let me highlight here how sociocracy looks at
      objections.<itemizedlist>
          <listitem>
            <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->The
            definition of an objection is: something a circle member flags
            that they believe shows that the proposal isn’t safe enough and
            will harm the circle in achieving its aim. Why would anyone ever
            object to a proposal? Because they care about the circle and about
            achieving its aim. Therefore, objections are precious and give you
            valuable information relevant to your work.</para>
          </listitem>

          <listitem>
            <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->We
            make sure to understand the objection. Sometimes we need more
            information from the person who objected, or ask them to be more
            specific in explaining their objection.</para>
          </listitem>

          <listitem>
            <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->As
            for steps, the facilitator may do a round where people can offer
            ideas, drawing from those options. Then the facilitation picks
            what they see as the most promising solution and makes a formal,
            new proposal. You start again in the consent process and repeat
            the pattern until there is consent.</para>
          </listitem>

          <listitem>
            <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->To
            integrate the objection, there are – at least! – three things you
            can do. (See list on page <xref linkend="objections"/><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->.)</para>
          </listitem>
        </itemizedlist></para>

      <informaltable>
        <!--Warning: passing through `tabular` element: -->

        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td><!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" yoffset="-0.9pt" --><mediaobject>
                <imageobject>
                  <imagedata fileref="illustrations/Image34.png" width="100%"/>
                </imageobject>
              </mediaobject></td>

            <td><!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><emphasis
            role="bold">Modify<!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: font="medium" -->
            Modify the proposal until the proposal is good enough for now.
            Shorten term<!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: font="medium" -->
            Shorten the term so you can carry out the proposal and evaluate
            whether it works. Pick a time frame that seems safe enough.
            Measure the concern<!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: font="medium" --></emphasis>
            <!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#46818D" fontsize="90%" -->Approve
            the proposal, <emphasis role="from-text">and</emphasis> add
            tracking concerning the objection. Example: if you are worried
            about the budget, keep a close eye on how money flows. If you are
            worried that a policy will confuse customers (therefore harming
            the aim of delivering service/products to them), find a metric
            that you could track to make sure you notice immediately if your
            concerns become true. Move ahead but with your eyes wide open</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </informaltable>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->The
      right to object needs to be taken seriously because it is essential to
      the collective steering process. The image I use is one of a boat on a
      river. The river flows, and we try to stay more or less in the middle of
      the river, floating along gently. Sometimes we might drift too far to
      one side, and then we might gently steer back towards the middle.
      Sometimes, we might not pay attention, or there’s a current, then we
      bump into the banks. It’s not a big deal – we simply find our way out
      again and continue our journey. The gentle steering process is what
      feedback is. The soft bump into the bank, that’s what objections are. We
      need them to steer.</para>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->For
      example, the right to object to new members is crucial – too many groups
      have been rendered dysfunctional because of toxic dynamics around
      individuals. It is also true for consenting to aims or the agenda of a
      meeting. Consent gives you shared power. You are now 100% responsible
      and empowered. Use that power!</para>

      <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: class="ltx_phantom" color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->blabla<!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" --></para>
    </section>

    <section>
      <title><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#46818D" font="sansserif" -->Your
      documents</title>

      <section>
        <title><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#808080" -->Aims
        and domains table</title>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->As
        you grow and mature, it will be good to clarify in more detail how you
        run things. The first important document is the aims and domains
        table, a written record of who has what authority and responsibility
        for what in the whole organization. Again, the aim describes what each
        circle is setting out to do. The domain is a list of “things” each
        circle has in its domain. As the organization grows and
        differentiates, aims and domains need to be updated and
        revised.</para>

        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Below
        are aims and domains of a fictional organization with 3 department
        circles and one sub-circle.</para>

