        <section>
          <title><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#808080" -->Governance
          documents</title>

          <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->To
          protect the governance system that you want to follow for the long
          run, it makes sense to write it down. Many conflicts in
          organizations come from a lack of clarity, so create clarity before
          conflict arises.</para>

          <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->There
          are three different kinds of documents.<itemizedlist>
              <listitem>
                <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->By-laws
                describe the interface of our organization with the legal
                sphere.</para>
              </listitem>

              <listitem>
                <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Governance
                agreement: a description of the governance system, for example
                how policy is made, a description of what consent is, how
                conflicts are resolved, etc.</para>
              </listitem>

              <listitem>
                <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Policies,
                often collected in a “policy manual” that hold our decisions,
                e.g. compensation policies, noise policies or whatever is
                needed to guide the organization’s and circles’
                operations.</para>
              </listitem>
            </itemizedlist><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->You
          can see see our growing online resources for templates for different
          sectors, countries, and situations.</para>
        </section>

        <section>
          <title><emphasis role="bold">8<!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#46818D" -->Now
          and forever</emphasis></title>

          <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->The
          main focus of this booklet are the basic patterns of governance and
          the mechanics of getting a functional, self-governing structure up
          and running.</para>

          <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->In
          addition, there are other topics you need to pay attention to as you
          operate, which closely interrelate with governance. The best list of
          those things to pay attention to that I am aware of are the Core
          Design Principles phrased by Prosocial, based on the work of Elinor
          Ostrom.</para>

          <section>
            <title><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#46818D" font="sansserif" -->Prosocial’s
            Core Design Principles.</title>

            <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Wouldn’t
            it be good if someone studied dozens and dozens of cooperatively
            run organizations all over the world to see what the successful
            ones do and what the not-so-successful ones lack? Then condense it
            into a list of criteria and share those? Well, the good news is
            that it has been done, and done well!</para>

            <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->These
            are the design principles that successful, cooperative
            organizations are below.</para>

            <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->For
            more information please see www.prosocial.world.</para>

            <informaltable>
              <!--Warning: passing through `tabular` element: -->

              <tbody>
                <tr>
                  <td><!--Warning: passing through `p` element: --><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" --><para>lightteal
                  <emphasis role="bold">Core design principles:
                  </emphasis></para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->
                  <orderedlist>
                      <listitem>
                        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Strong
                        group identity &amp; understanding of purpose</para>
                      </listitem>

                      <listitem>
                        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Fair
                        distribution of costs &amp; benefits</para>
                      </listitem>

                      <listitem>
                        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Inclusive
                        decision making</para>
                      </listitem>

                      <listitem>
                        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Peer-based
                        monitoring of agreed upon behaviors</para>
                      </listitem>

                      <listitem>
                        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Graduated
                        responding to behaviors</para>
                      </listitem>

                      <listitem>
                        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Fair
                        &amp; fast conflict resolution</para>
                      </listitem>

                      <listitem>
                        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Authority
                        to self-govern (according to CDP1-6)</para>
                      </listitem>

                      <listitem>
                        <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Appropriate
                        relations with other group</para>
                      </listitem>
                    </orderedlist></td>
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </informaltable>

            <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->A
            few comments, also adding a sociocratic perspective are in the
            below sections.</para>

            <section>
              <title><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#808080" -->CDP
              1: Purpose and shared identity</title>

              <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Strong
              group identity and purpose is what I understand as the mission
              and aim. As you have seen in this booklet, the aim is the
              ‘initial spark’ that makes a group. It’s the invitation and the
              shared, explicitly agreed-upon aim of the group.</para>

              <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Note
              that any self-managed organization can change and adjust its aim
              if there is consent.</para>

              <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Yet,
              it’s the purpose that centers all the activity and the choices
              made. That means that, especially in the long run, every
              organization needs to make sure that new members are fully aware
              of the aims of the organization and the circle they are joining.
              Be sure to add this to your onboarding plan and membership
              processes.</para>
            </section>

            <section>
              <title><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#808080" -->CDP
              2: Fair distribution of costs and benefits</title>

              <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->From
              a sociocratic perspective, these are conversations and decisions
              that need to be made on a policy level. For example, in a fully
              formed organization, a membership circle may host the
              conversation of “what are our expectations of volunteers?”
              Similarly, in a paid organization, compensation policies have to
              be worked out with a lot of feedback from all affected people.
              Be sure to talk about which domains those topics are held in to
              create clarity and a place where exploration can happen and
              people can give feedback if they are unhappy with the current
              status.</para>

              <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->If
              you are forming a volunteer group, creating the domains for
              financial decisions might be further in the future. If you are
              starting a business, you need to create that clarity early
              on.</para>
            </section>

            <section>
              <title><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#808080" -->CDP
              3: Inclusive decision making</title>

              <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Using
              consent and linking, your decision making is probably already
              above average! The only thing to keep in mind is to make sure
              information flows well. The circles and consent only affect
              circle members, but you might have supporting members or simply
              members of other circles that need to be heard on matters that
              affect them. The responsibility of every circle includes getting
              outside feedback.</para>
            </section>

            <section>
              <title><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#808080" -->CDP
              4 &amp; 5: Feedback &amp; accountability</title>

              <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Note
              that I am bundling two different principles here because they go
              hand in hand quite often. The question here is, how do we share
              information if something isn’t working, and how do we hold
              people accountable?</para>

              <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Both
              of these principles are woven into the practice, governance, and
              culture of our organizations. Sociocratic formats like reviews,
              selections, and meeting evaluations are wonderful, intentional
              feedback moments. Yet, it’s still people who need to make sure
              they get scheduled and taken seriously. I always say, meeting
              evaluations are good moments like sociocracy gives you the stage
              – but you have to decide to get up there!</para>

              <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->In
              my experience, a commitment to feedback is the hardest principle
              for people to stick to – they’d rather avoid it. That’s why it’s
              good to not only stick to the processes but also, from time to
              time, renew our commitment to taking in feedback. Feedback is a
              way to smoothen our collaboration and to re-align ourselves with
              each other and our new members.</para>

              <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->A
              sociocratic organization needs to be willing to defend its own
              functioning against inhibiting factors. For example, each circle
              has to be able to say no to people or even exclude them from a
              circle. (More about that in the sociocracy manual <emphasis
              role="from-text">Many Voices One Song.</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->)
              We need to work into our policies how we hold people accountable
              if that becomes necessary.</para>

              <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->There
              are small things that make things easier. For example, the
              backlog is a great way to improve a circle’s own accountability,
              as well as tiny practices like checking who is present and who
              is filling what role in the ADMIN phase. It’s often the small
              stuff that starts to add up and lets people disengage from the
              work. Catch it, and improve it.</para>
            </section>

            <section>
              <title><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#808080" -->CDP
              6: Fair &amp; fast conflict resolution</title>

              <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Every
              organization needs its own institutional support of conflict
              resolution. This is not only practical but also, in my view, a
              logical consequence of decentralized governance. You have to be
              able to address conflict in a decentralized way, wherever it
              might occur. In self-governance, there is no outside source of
              truth so working things out with each other is key to being and
              remaining a self-healing organization.</para>

              <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Most
              sociocratic organizations I know hold the values of restorative
              justice – connection and support over punishment. Many embrace
              Nonviolent Communication (NVC). Both tools are based on
              listening and 100% co-responsibility and shared power. There are
              great tools out there – use them wisely, use them often! The two
              aspects here are:<itemizedlist>
                  <listitem>
                    <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Personal
                    skills: how well is each individual or group prepared to
                    act when there is conflict?</para>
                  </listitem>

                  <listitem>
                    <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Institutional
                    support: What systems does the organization offer overall
                    to support conflict resolution overall?</para>
                  </listitem>
                </itemizedlist><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->To
              start, it’s a good idea to define which circle holds the domain
              of conflict resolution. Then that circle can figure out how to
              operationalize it for everyone.</para>

              <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->In
              my experience, an organization needs more than one avenue to
              address this conflict resolution well – but what it might look
              like highly depends on the context and culture. For example, an
              organization may make NVC training a requirement before joining
              or provide ongoing training for members. There might be a role
              of internal mediators or internal coaching to clarify
              disagreements before they grow into conflicts. There might be
              worksheets for internal work, buddy systems, online resources –
              start with a reasonable and doable solution, implement it,
              evaluate their effectiveness, and improve from there!</para>
            </section>

            <section>
              <title><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#808080" -->CDP
              7: Authority to self-govern</title>

              <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->This
              is an interesting one – and it may not be immediately obvious to
              you. This core design principle points to the fact that a
              self-governed organization will struggle if there is too much
              interference from the outside that the organization itself does
              not have control over. A good example is legal incorporation and
              models of ownership. You might never need this with your
              project, but sometimes it is hard for fully formed organizations
              to incorporate in a sociocratic way that matches their values.
              So in a way, it is the legal system that negatively impacts the
              freedom of a self-governing organization to determine how they
              want to do things.</para>

              <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->For
              example, what if the law says there has to be a board, and they
              have to make decisions by majority vote – but the organization
              wants to make decisions by consent and hold the power in the
              General Circle and its sub-circles? There are no dealbreakers
              here, but sometimes a little bit of a workaround is necessary.
              The same can be said for grant-givers or donors that want to
              determine how you run things – always make sure to create a
              context for your organization that gives you as much freedom and
              flexibility as possible and only adds limitations that you can
              integrate.</para>
            </section>

            <section>
              <title><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#808080" -->CDP
              8: Appropriate relations to other groups</title>

              <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->This
              is more fun! As an organization, not only keep your context-free
              from negative interferences but also enhance your system with
              positive influence. For example, form partnerships, coalitions
              and invite others to be members of your Mission Circle. Meet
              other groups and keep things open and inviting.</para>

              <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->For
              more information and more ideas on how to keep a tap on these
              key design principles, see Prosocial’s work!</para>
            </section>
          </section>

          <section>
            <title><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#46818D" font="sansserif" -->Additional
            tools</title>

            <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Sociocracy
            is a governance system, not a magic fix for everyone. There are
            tons of processes out there that can enhance your practice and
            complement your governance processes.</para>

            <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->There
            are many good social technologies like Art of Hosting (incl. Open
            Space), Agile, Lean, Theory U, Permaculture, design thinking,
            Dragon Dreaming, Acceptance and Commitment Therapy (ACT), The
            Work, The Work That Reconnects, and the psychological flexibility
            it brings…the list is long and full of wonderful, holistic
            practices.</para>

            <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Most
            of them work best in the realm of surfacing deeper information and
            more ideas. They can best be used in explorations, for example, to
            surface possible project ideas or to analyze issues more deeply.
            In a way, your circle might make a wonderful “excursion” to take a
            deep dive into a topic using some social technology, and then you
            turn your output into backlog items (for new ideas to tackle) or
            proposals (for potential solutions). That’s when sociocracy kicks
            in again to bring the decision over the finish line!</para>
          </section>

          <section>
            <title><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#46818D" font="sansserif" -->Let
            the circle be unbroken</title>

            <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->I
            want to share one thought for you as an <emphasis
            role="from-text">oh!</emphasis><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->-moment
            that I owe to by colleague John Buck. Imagine a single circle –
            like your group of founders.</para>

            <informalfigure>
              <mediaobject>
                <imageobject>
                  <imagedata fileref="illustrations/Image35a.png" width="100%"/>
                </imageobject>
              </mediaobject>

              <mediaobject>
                <imageobject>
                  <imagedata fileref="illustrations/Image35b.png" width="100%"/>
                </imageobject>
              </mediaobject>
            </informalfigure>

            <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->That
            circle is like a group of people holding hands – an unbroken
            circle of people who are working together as equals.</para>

            <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->Now,
            if you add another circle and you have two people (leader and
            delegate) between this double-linked circle, then the circle of
            people “holding hands” is still unbroken.</para>

            <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->The
            same is still true even if you add dozens or hundreds of circles.
            In the image on the right, imagine the dark line was a group of
            people holding hands. They could all step back more and more until
            they are forming a big circle – a circle of peers,
            connected.</para>

            <para><!--Warning: text element with unused attributes: color="#000000" fontsize="90%" -->We
            are always one.</para>

            <informalfigure>
              <mediaobject>
                <imageobject>
                  <imagedata fileref="illustrations/Image36.png" width="100%"/>
                </imageobject>
